{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox writer | name = Munir Niazi | image = Mr. Muneer Niazi.jpg | caption = Niazi reciting his ghazal | pseudonym = | birth_name = Munir Ahmed Niazi | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1928|04|9}} | birth_place = [[Hoshiarpur|Khanpur]], [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]], [[British India]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2006|12|26|1928|04|09}} | death_place = [[Lahore]], [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]] | occupation = [[Urdu poet]], [[Punjabi poet]] | nationality = [[Pakistan]]i | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = [[Govt. Sadiq Egerton College Bahawalpur]] [[Dayal Singh College, Lahore]] | period = 1960 - 2006 (active years) | genre = [[Urdu]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] [[Poetry]] | subject = | movement = | notableworks = | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | awards = [[Sitara-e-Imtiaz]] in 2005 <ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.dawn.com/news/367548/130-nationals-foreigners-to-get-civil-awards | title=130 nationals, foreigners to get civil awards | newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] | date=14 August 2004 | accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> | signature = | website = | portaldisp = | imagesize = }}
'''Munir Ahmad''', better known as '''Munir Niazi''', ({{lang-pa|{{Nastaliq|منیر نیازی }}}})(1928-2006) [[Sitara-e-Imtiaz]] Award recipient, was an [[Urdu]] and [[Punjabi poet]] from [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zemtv.com/2013/12/27/unique-interview-of-munir-niazi-taken-by-pervin-shakir/ |publisher=zemtv.com |title=UNIQUE INTERVIEW OF MUNIR NIAZI TAKEN BY PERVIN SHAKIR |date=2013-12-27 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref> Originally of Pashtun descent, Munir Ahmed used to call himself [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]] as Punjabi definition is cultural and geographical and most of his poetry also reflected the culture of Punjab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khybernews.tv/newsDetails.php?cat=12&key=NDkxMTc= |publisher=Rediff.com |title=7th death anniversary of Munir Niazi today |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>
==Biography== Niazi was born on 9 April 1928, in Khanpur, one of the Pathan villages in [[Hoshiarpur]] [[Punjab]], [[British India]]. He was initially educated at Khanpur. After the [[partition of India]] in 1947, he migrated and settled in [[Sahiwal]], where he passed his [[matriculation]] examination. He earned an intermediate degree from Sadiq Egerton College, [[Bahawalpur]] and a B.A. degree from [[Dayal Singh College, Lahore]], [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1098878 |publisher=dawn.com newspaper |title=A fitting tribute to Munir Niazi |date=2014-04-10 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref> Munir Niazi launched a weekly, ''Seven Colours'', from Sahiwal in 1949. Some of his poetry was used in films and these film songs became extremely popular super-hit songs among the [[Pakistani]] public which established him as the foremost movie songwriter of [[Pakistan]]. For example, the film song in film Shaheed (1962), ''Uss Bewafa Ka Shehar Hai Aur Hum Hain Dosto'' and many others.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0375056/soundtrack?ref_=tt_trv_snd, Munir Niazi hit film song on IMDb website, Retrieved 17 March 2016</ref>
==His poetry that became super-hit film songs==
{|class="wikitable" |- !Film song !!Singers !!Song lyrics by !! Music by !!Film and year |- |"Jis Ne Mere Dil Ko Dard Diya"<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3usvE65IzG8, Munir Niazi song on YouTube, Retrieved 18 March 2016</ref> |[[Mehdi Hassan]] |'''Munir Niazi''' |Hasan Latif Lilak |Susral (1962) |- |"Jaa Apni Hasraton Pe Aansoo Baha Ke Sau Jaa" |[[Noor Jehan]] |'''Munir Niazi''' |Hasan Latif Lilak |Susral (1962) |- |"Kaisay Kaisay Loag Hamare Jee Ko Jalanay Aa Jaatain Hain" |[[Mehdi Hassan]] |'''Munir Niazi''' |Hasan Latif Lilak |Tere Shehar Mein (1965) |- |"Zinda Rahein Tau Kaya Hai Jau Mar Jaaen Hum Tau Kaya" |[[Naheed Akhtar]] |'''Munir Niazi''' |[[M Ashraf]] |Kharidar (1976) |- |}
He also wrote for newspapers, magazines and radio. In 1960, he established a publication institute, ''Al-Misal''. He was later associated with [[Pakistan Television]], [[Lahore]] and lived in Lahore till his death. ''Taiz Hawa Aur Tanha Phool, Jungle Mein Dhanak, Dushmanoon Kai Darmiyan Sham'' and ''Mah-e-Munir'' are some of his [[Urdu language|Urdu]] publications. In Punjabi language, he has published ''Safar Di Raat, Char Chup Cheezan and Rasta Dassan Walay Tarey.'' Effective imagery in his poetry conveys pictures in a few words.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awaztoday.com/News_Munir-Niazis-5th-death-anniversary-today_3_16027_Showbiz-News.aspx |publisher=awaztoday.com |title=Munir Niazi’s 5th death anniversary today |date=2011-12-20 |accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref> He has experimented with poetic forms and has tried to create a new [[Style (literature)|style]], [[rhythm]] and [[diction]] in [[Urdu]] poetry. Innocence, mythology, nostalgia, dreams, eroticism, and romance are some of his most common themes. Selected English translations of Munir Niazi's poetical works were edited by Suhail Safdar and published in 1996.<ref>{{cite book |first=Suhail |last=Safdar |title=The Poetical Works of Munir Niazi, Pakistan Writings |year=1996}}</ref>
Munir Niazi died of [[Respiratory#Conditions of the respiratory system|respiratory illness]] on 26 December 2006 in [[Lahore]], [[Pakistan]].<ref>http://www.dawn.com/news/1153292, Munir Niazi death anniversary being observed today, Dawn newspaper, published 26 Dec 2014, Retrieved 17 March 2016</ref>
